  "prompt": "Can a woman get pregnant a few days before her period and still have period?",
  "response": "While it is possible to get pregnant during this time, it's less likely. However, some women may experience what appears to be a period but is actually breakthrough bleeding or light spotting during early pregnancy. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Fertility window: Most women ovulate about 14 days before their period starts, but this can vary.\n\n2. Chance of pregnancy: The days just before a period are typically considered less fertile, but it's not impossible to get pregnant.\n\n3. Irregular periods: Some women have irregular cycles, which can make predicting fertility more challenging.\n\n4. Breakthrough bleeding: Some pregnant women experience light bleeding that can be mistaken for a period.\n\n5. Recommendation: If pregnancy is a concern, it's best to:\n- Use reliable contraception\n- Take a pregnancy test if periods are missed\n- Consult a healthcare professional for personalized advice\n\nRemember that every woman's body is different, and cycle timing can vary.",
